  <static seed="235" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions10.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{5}{9} + \frac{25}{27}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{40}{27}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator.</p>
<p>In this case, the least common multiple of <m>9</m> and <m>27</m> is <m>27</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{\frac{5}{9}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>27</m>, we multiply <m>3</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned} \frac{5}{9} \amp = \frac{5 \cdot 3}{9 \cdot 3}\\ \amp  = \frac{15}{27} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>The second fraction already has the common denominator.</p>
<p>Finally, we can do the addition. The whole process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{5}{9} + \frac{25}{27}
        \amp = \frac{15}{27} + \frac{25}{27} \\
        \amp = \frac{15 + 25}{27} \\
        \amp = \frac{40}{27}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer is  <m>\displaystyle{\frac{40}{27}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
